excerpt: Busy Saturday market with vendors for food, produce, art, clothing & Tasmanian timber items.
detail_description: Salamanca Market is a bustling Saturday market in Hobart, Tasmania, known for its diverse offerings. With over 300 vendors, the market features an array of products including food, produce, art, clothing and Tasmanian timber items. The vibrant atmosphere along the waterfront showcases locally crafted goods such as unique clothing and jewelry, artisan cheeses, fresh produce and more.
name: Salamanca Market

excerpt:
Battery Point is a suburb of the city of Hobart, Tasmania, Australia. It is immediately south of the central business district. It is in the local government area of City of Hobart.
Battery Point is named after the battery of guns which were established on the point in 1818 as part of the Hobart coastal defences. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Battery Point, a suburb of Hobart in Tasmania, Australia, is known for its historic houses dating back to the first European settlement. The area offers a variety of activities such as visiting art galleries and weekly markets, dining at fabulous restaurants, and taking in the spectacular views from Mount Wellington.
name: Battery Point

excerpt: A 14-hectare site established in 1818 offering historic plants, a visitor centre & a cafe.
detail_description: The Royal Tasmanian Botanical Gardens, established in 1818, cover a 14-hectare site on Hobart's waterfront along the River Derwent. It is a popular attraction for families with plenty of trails and green space for kids to enjoy. The gardens feature historic plants, a Japanese garden, an Antarctic plant house, a fuchsia house, a cactus collection, and a traditional herb garden.
name: Royal Tasmanian Botanical Gardens
address: Lower Domain Rd, Hobart TAS 7000, Australia

detail_description: Mona, the Museum of Old and New Art in Hobart, is a must-visit attraction for families. It's Australia's largest privately owned museum with captivating modern and historic art installations that are both confronting and entertaining. One of the recommended ways to get there is by taking the Mona Roma ferry, which offers a relaxing and picturesque ride along the River Derwent. The ferry trip takes approximately 25 minutes from Brooke Street Pier and provides great commentary along with comfortable seating.
name: Mona Ferry

excerpt: Established museum featuring art, cultural & science exhibitions, along with a courtyard cafe.
detail_description: Nestled in the historic waterfront precinct of Hobart, the Tasmanian Museum and Art Gallery (TMAG) offers a delightful blend of art, culture, and science. As Australia's second oldest museum, it presents an engaging array of exhibits that delve into Tasmania's rich history. Visitors can explore Indigenous Aboriginal culture, learn about the elusive Tasmanian Tiger, and admire colonial arts and crafts.
name: Tasmanian Museum and Art Gallery

excerpt: Lively Sunday hub of vendors selling area-sourced fare such as seasonal produce & baked goods.
detail_description: Farm Gate Market is a lively and bustling Sunday market located in central Hobart, Tasmania. It offers an abundance of fresh, locally sourced produce including seasonal fruits and vegetables, artisanal cheeses, homemade breads and pastas, free-range meats and eggs, freshly caught oysters, and handcrafted gins from local distilleries. The market also features a variety of vendors selling pickles, relishes, jams as well as breakfast and lunch options such as oversized cookies and gourmet toasties.
name: Farm Gate Market

excerpt: 1830 edifice serving as a chapel, jail & court for male convicts, with an execution yard & gallows.
detail_description: Hobart Convict Penitentiary, located in the heart of Hobart's CBD, is a historic site that offers a glimpse into Tasmania's early period. This 1830 edifice served as a chapel, jail, and court for male convicts and features an execution yard and gallows. Designed by architect John Lee Archer, the Georgian prison building housed around 40,000 male convicts until convict transportation ceased in 1853.
name: Hobart Convict Penitentiary
address: Corner of Campbell and, Brisbane St, Hobart TAS 7000, Australia

excerpt: Replica of the huts used in Antarctica by Douglas Mawson & his team, plus stories of the expedition.
detail_description: The Mawson's Huts Replica Museum in Hobart is a faithful recreation of the huts used by Douglas Mawson and his team during their Antarctic expedition. Located just 200 meters from where the expedition departed in 1911, this museum offers an immersive experience into the living conditions of Australia's early Antarctic explorers.
name: Mawson's Huts Replica Museum
address: Morrison St &, Argyle St, Hobart TAS 7000, Australia

excerpt: Hobart, capital of Australia's island state of Tasmania, sits on the River Derwent. At its fashionable Salamanca Place, old sandstone warehouses host galleries and cafes. Nearby is Battery Point, a historic district with narrow lanes and colonial-era cottages. The city's backdrop is 1,270m-high Mount Wellington, with sweeping views, plus hiking and cycling trails.
detail_description: Hobart, the capital of Tasmania, Australia's island state, is nestled along the River Derwent. The city features the trendy Salamanca Place, where historic sandstone warehouses have been transformed into galleries and cafes. Nearby Battery Point showcases a charming historic district with narrow lanes and colonial-era cottages. Mount Wellington provides a stunning backdrop to the city, offering sweeping views and various outdoor activities such as hiking and cycling trails.
name: Hobart

excerpt: Vibrant street featuring art galleries, cafes, bars & theaters, plus a bustling outdoor market.
detail_description: Salamanca Pl is a lively street in Hobart, known for its art galleries, cafes, bars, and theaters. The Wild Island gallery showcases various artworks including Tasmanian sustainable wood design, textiles, ceramics, and jewelry. It also features a diverse selection of ethically produced gifts from Tasmania. Visitors can explore boutique shops and eateries offering artisanal products such as cheeses, pork products, preserves, chocolates, and more.
name: Salamanca Pl

excerpt: Collection of artifacts & displays on the state's nautical history, including whaling & shipwrecks.
detail_description: The Maritime Museum of Tasmania, located in the Carnegie Building at Sullivans Cove, offers a comprehensive look into the nautical history of the state. The museum showcases the significance of seafaring in Tasmanian life, from indigenous maritime connections to early European exploration and 19th-century maritime industries like whaling. With over 70,000 objects including photography, art, historical artifacts, archives and intricate models, this museum provides an informative and immersive experience.
name: Maritime Museum of Tasmania

excerpt: Georgian theatre with a red-and-gold interior staging modern plays, dance and performing arts shows.
detail_description: The Theatre Royal in Hobart is a Georgian theater known for its stunning red-and-gold interior. It hosts a variety of modern plays, dance performances, and shows related to the performing arts. As one of the oldest continually operating theaters in Australia, dating back to 1837, it holds historical significance and offers visitors a unique cultural experience. This iconic venue is just one of many historical sites worth exploring in the Hobart region, showcasing Tasmania's rich heritage and diverse attractions.
name: Theatre Royal, Hobart
address: Entry via The Hedberg, corner of Campbell &, 29 Campbell Street, Collins St, Hobart TAS 7000, Australia

detail_description: St. David's Park, located near the bustling Salamanca Markets in Hobart, is a green oasis with large trees providing plenty of shade and peaceful spots to relax and read. The park features amenities like flying foxes for kids, a spider web, and a soccer/cricket oval. It is a popular venue for birthday parties and sports games. The park also has historical significance as it was once Hobart's first cemetery, with old headstones embedded into its walls. St.
name: St. David's Park

detail_description: Located in Salamanca Place, the Parliament House in Tasmania is a historic Georgian building constructed in 1840. It was initially used as a customs house and later transitioned into serving as the parliament building. The structure, made of local sandstone by convict labor, offers guided tours twice a day on non-sitting weekdays. Visitors can explore its rich history and architectural significance while enjoying the central and easily accessible location.
name: Parliament House

detail_description: Dark Mofo is one of the most unique and talked-about arts festivals in Australia, held in Hobart. The event features offbeat theatre productions, light shows, classic films, and late-night openings of MONA. It's a must-see experience with a sea of red lighting and fire elements that create a stunning atmosphere. Visitors can also enjoy the Dark Mofo food festival with amazing food, wine, and distillers.
name: Dark Mofo

excerpt: Bustling dock with converted colonial buildings housing galleries, seafood restaurants & shops.
detail_description: Constitution Dock, located on the Derwent River in Hobart, is a bustling area with converted colonial buildings that house galleries, seafood restaurants, and shops. It holds historical significance as the location where Hobart's founding document was signed. The dock is also famous for being the finish line of the Sydney to Hobart Yacht Race and features private yachts, fishing boats, historic buildings, and ships from past commercial activities.
name: Constitution Dock

excerpt: Cultural space in a historic setting offering art galleries & artist studios, plus theaters & shops.
detail_description: Salamanca Arts Centre is a cultural hub located in a historic setting at Salamanca Place, Hobart. It houses various art galleries, artist studios, theaters, and shops. Visitors can explore the diverse works of local artists in mediums such as painting, photography, ceramics, and jewelry-making at galleries like Long Gallery, Nolan Gallery, Off Centre, Spacebar Gallery and Sidespace Gallery. The center offers an immersive experience for art enthusiasts with its range of artistic expressions and design retailers.
name: Salamanca Arts Centre
address: 77 Salamanca Pl, Battery Point TAS 7004, Australia

excerpt: North Hobart is a suburb of the city of Hobart, Tasmania, Australia. As its name suggests, it lies directly north of the Hobart City Centre. Wikipedia.
detail_description: North Hobart, a suburb of Hobart, Tasmania, Australia, is located just north of the CBD. Once considered rough and downmarket, it has transformed into a vibrant and creative neighborhood catering to hipsters and trendy residents. The area offers some of the best cafes, bars, and restaurants in Hobart. One popular spot is Dede Indonesian & Thai Cuisine on Elizabeth Street which serves authentic Asian dishes including spicy curries and seafood specials.
name: North Hobart

detail_description: Street Eats @ Franko is a vibrant and eclectic food bazaar located at Franklin Square in Hobart. It takes place every Friday evening from November to April, offering an array of delicious street food, drinks, and live music. The market features a variety of food trucks and stalls serving up everything from seafood paella to wallaby burgers. Visitors can enjoy the lively atmosphere with picnic rugs provided for relaxation.
name: Street Eats @ Franko
address: Franklin Square, 70 Macquarie St, Hobart TAS 7000, Australia

detail_description: Sullivans Cove, located in Hobart, Tasmania, is home to Australia's most awarded whisky distillery. The distillery has received numerous accolades at the World Whiskies Awards for its exceptional single malts. Visitors can enjoy tasting flights of whiskies and take a tour of the distillery at its location in Cambridge. Despite being situated in an industrial estate, the distillery and tasting room offer a magical experience for whisky enthusiasts.
name: Sullivans Cove

detail_description: St David's Cathedral, located in the heart of Hobart, Tasmania, is a splendid Anglican church dating back to the mid-19th century. The cathedral boasts outstanding architecture with stained glass windows and wooden beams. It offers regular services and features a small museum area as well as seasonal religious events. Visitors can enjoy the cathedral's Georgian style design and take in its beauty from Murray Street.
name: St David's Cathedral

excerpt: Built in 1866, this oak-lined urban park offers seating, restrooms, a giant chess board & fountain.
detail_description: Franklin Square, established in 1866, is a charming urban park with beautiful oak trees and various amenities such as seating, restrooms, a giant chess board, and a fountain. The park also hosts the popular Street Eats @ Franko event every Friday evening, featuring food trucks and stalls around the fountain area along with live music performances. Additionally, the square holds historical significance as it has been home to Tasmania's government administration since colonial times.
name: Franklin Square

detail_description: Evolve Spirits Bar is an upscale and stylish lounge located in Hobart's MACq 01 hotel. It has been recognized as Australia's Hotel Bar of the Year and Tasmania's Cocktail Bar of the Year in 2021. The bar features a unique decor with dinosaur fossils, creating a charming and historic atmosphere. With over 600 premium spirits showcased on its golden bar shelf, Evolve offers a wide selection of cocktails for guests to enjoy.
name: Evolve Spirits Bar

detail_description: Queens Domain is a beautiful parkland in Hobart, Tasmania, offering stunning views of the city and surrounding areas. It features lush greenery, walking trails, and picnic spots for visitors to enjoy. The park is home to various native plants and wildlife, providing a peaceful escape from the hustle and bustle of urban life. With its well-maintained grounds and recreational facilities, Queens Domain is a perfect destination for nature lovers and outdoor enthusiasts.
name: Queens Domain

detail_description: Brooke Street Pier is a remarkable floating pontoon located on the south side of Sullivans Cove at Franklin Wharf. This 80-meter-long and 20-meter-wide structure serves as a high-tech ferry terminal and a market space for Tasmanian produce, specialty foods, artisanal alcohol, design items, and cosmetics.
name: Brooke Street Pier

detail_description: The Hobart Twilight Market is a lively event that takes place every Friday evening during the summer months, offering a vibrant mix of local food and drink vendors, live music, and a strong community atmosphere. Visitors can sample an array of Tasmanian flavors and locally sourced produce from various street food vendors. In addition to the culinary delights, the market also showcases local artisans and designers, providing a comprehensive experience of Hobart's dynamic community.
name: Hobart Twilight Market

detail_description: Hobart Waterfront Apartments are a popular choice for travelers seeking a central location and a maritime atmosphere. Somerset on the Pier, located in a converted 1930s pier building, provides apartment-style rooms and loft suites with views of historic Sullivans Cove. Meanwhile, Salamanca Wharf Hotel offers contemporary accommodations adjacent to the vibrant Salamanca Place and its famous markets, making it an excellent option for couples and discerning travelers.
name: Hobart Waterfront Apartments

detail_description: LARK Cellar Door in Hobart is a must-visit spot for those looking to experience the best of Tasmania's craft beers and spirits. Crafty Hobart By Night, hosted at Lark Cellar Door and Whisky Bar on Thursdays and Saturdays, offers a laid-back atmosphere where visitors can indulge in local craft beers and sample delectable dishes from various vendors.
name: LARK Cellar Door, Hobart

detail_description: Explore the rich history of Hobart by taking a stroll along the Battery Point Sculpture Trail. This hour-long walk showcases nine large art pieces that symbolize various aspects of Hobart and Tasmania's past, such as weight, measurement, time, quantity, date or distance. Each sculpture tells a unique story about the region's history. Before embarking on this cultural journey, indulge in some waterfront fish and chips to fuel up for your leisurely amble.
name: Battery Point Sculpture Trail

excerpt: South Hobart is one of Hobart's inner suburbs. It is bound by Dynnyrne, Fern Tree, West Hobart and the Hobart City Centre. Wikipedia.
detail_description: South Hobart, located within the inner suburbs of Hobart, is surrounded by Dynnyrne, Fern Tree, West Hobart and the Hobart City Centre. This charming neighborhood offers a mix of residential areas and natural beauty. With its proximity to various other suburbs and attractions in Hobart, South Hobart provides a convenient base for exploring the city's diverse offerings.
name: South Hobart

excerpt: Exhibits on British colonialera & historic military engagements in barracks from the early 1800s.
detail_description: The Army Museum of Tasmania is a captivating destination that immerses visitors in the rich tapestry of Australia's military history, particularly highlighting the contributions of Tasmanian soldiers and regiments. Housed in a former military jail dating back to the early 1800s, this community-owned museum offers an intimate look at various conflicts that have shaped Australia, including both World Wars, the Korean War, Vietnam War, and more recent engagements like those in Afghanistan.
name: Army Museum of Tasmania
address: Anglesea Barracks, 96-120 Davey St, Hobart TAS 7000, Australia

excerpt: Commercial gallery exhibiting & selling paintings, prints & jewelry by Aboriginal artists.
detail_description: Art Mob - Aboriginal Fine Art is a commercial gallery located in Hobart, showcasing and selling a diverse range of paintings, prints, sculptures, and jewelry created by both established and emerging Aboriginal artists. With over a decade of experience, the passionate team at Art Mob is dedicated to promoting the rich diversity of Aboriginal fine art. The gallery specializes in works by Tasmanian Aboriginal artists and offers visitors an opportunity to explore and purchase authentic pieces at reasonable prices.
name: Art Mob - Aboriginal Fine Art

detail_description: Hobart Cenotaph, the main war memorial in Tasmania, offers a serene and humbling experience as visitors pay their respects to the fallen. Situated on a hilltop just outside the city center, it provides decent views of the river and Tasman Bridge. The site's pristine work and respectful ambiance make it a unique place to remember those who sacrificed themselves for peace and freedom.
name: Hobart Cenotaph
address: Anzac Parade, Queens Domain TAS 7000, Australia

detail_description: Government House Tasmania is a stunning Victorian building with original interiors and furniture. Visitors can take a tour of the house, including the gardens, orchard, and vineyard. It's an opportunity to meet the governor and her partner in person. The house overlooks the Royal Tasmanian Botanical Gardens and offers a glimpse into Tasmania's history and architecture.
name: Government House Tasmania
address: 7 Lower Domain Rd, Queens Domain TAS 7000, Australia

detail_description: Discover the best of Hobart and its surroundings with Red Decker Company's double-decker bus tour. With 20 different stops, you can explore cultural sights and attractions at your own pace. The hop-on-hop-off service allows for flexibility, valid for 24 or 48 hours depending on your ticket. Enjoy friendly drivers and informative guided talks available in multiple languages. Don't miss the Mt Wellington package for breathtaking views from the top with ample time to explore and take photos.
name: Red Decker Company
address: Brooke Street Pier, Hobart TAS 7000, Australia

detail_description: Coal River Farm is a delightful destination where visitors can savor freshly made food straight from the farm. The venue offers the unique experience of witnessing food being prepared right before your eyes, and even provides opportunities to learn about the process. Guests can enjoy delectable handmade cheese, chocolate, and locally sourced produce in the on-site restaurant. Additionally, there's an option to pick your own berries for a truly immersive experience.
name: Coal River Farm
address: Cat and Fiddle Arcade, 18A/60 Elizabeth St, Hobart TAS 7000, Australia

name: Doone Kennedy Hobart Aquatic Centre
address: 1 Davies Ave, Queens Domain TAS 7000, Australia

detail_description: The Tasmanian Symphony Orchestra is a cultural institution in Hobart, Australia's oldest theatre, the Theatre Royal. The orchestra performs at various venues including the Hobart Town Hall and offers a diverse range of events. They also host free outdoor concerts and perform in rural Tasmania as well as in schools and community centers to promote cultural experiences and education. Additionally, they collaborate with top-level visiting artists for their performances. The orchestra's commitment to spreading cultural experiences is evident through their varied performances and outreach efforts.
name: Tasmanian Symphony Orchestra
address: Federation Concert Hall, Ground Floor/1 Davey St, Hobart TAS 7000, Australia

excerpt: As Tasmanias capital, Hobart features a charming waterfront area with cobblestone streets and busy markets, along with historic sandstone warehouses now housing hip cafes and galleries. A trio of museums includes the Maritime Museum of Tasmania. Adventurous diners kayak out to order fish and chips from harbour fish punts, while ale and spirit fans visit area breweries and distilleries for craft beers and whisky.
detail_description: Hobart, the capital of Tasmania, boasts a picturesque waterfront area with cobblestone streets and bustling markets. The historic sandstone warehouses have been transformed into trendy cafes and galleries, adding to the city's charm. Visitors can explore a trio of museums including the Maritime Museum of Tasmania. For a unique dining experience, adventurous foodies can kayak to harbor fish punts to order fish and chips.
name: Hobart

detail_description: Plan your trip to Tasmania in August to coincide with the Beaker Street Festival, a renowned science and arts celebration held during National Science Week. The festival offers a variety of engaging activities such as an Antarctic polar plunge and sauna experience, a futuristic Future Foods dinner, and insightful talks by prominent Australian scientists like Dr. Karl and Adam Spencer. This event promises an unforgettable experience for science enthusiasts and curious minds alike.
name: Beaker Street Festival
address: 91/93 Macquarie St, West Hobart TAS 7000, Australia

detail_description: Located in the picturesque Coal River Valley near the historic town of Richmond, Zoodoo offers a range of exciting experiences and opportunities for interaction. Visitors can enjoy daily educational talks by keepers, as well as access to a newly upgraded cafe, gift shop, and a spacious indoor adventure playground.
name: Richmond Fellowship

detail_description: Tasmania's Taste of Summer, also known as The Taste of Tasmanian Festival, is a vibrant annual event in Hobart that showcases the finest offerings from the region. This festival features an array of Tasmanian food, wine, beer, and music. Visitors can explore tasting tables and food stalls at Hobart's Princes Wharf while browsing through arts, crafts, and artisan stalls.
name: Tasmania's Taste of Summer
address: 9 Castray Esplanade, Battery Point TAS 7004, Australia

detail_description: Liverpool St is a bustling shopping destination where you can explore Elizabeth Street Pier and indulge in a variety of retail therapy. For cider enthusiasts, a visit to Willie Smiths Apple Shed in Huon Valley, just 30 minutes from the city, offers a delightful lunch experience paired with refreshing ciders. Cap off your day with a delectable dinner at Franks, an Argentinian restaurant known for its excellent steaks and flavorful vegetable side dishes.
name: Liverpool St

detail_description: Van Diemens Land Creamery, established in 2005 by a Tasmanian dairy farming family, offers artisan ice cream made with fresh milk from their farm. Located on Hobart Waterfront, the creamery is a popular spot known for its delicious and unique flavors. Despite the long queues, visitors are willing to wait for a taste of their delightful ice creams.
name: Van Diemens Land Creamery
address: Constitution Dock, 2 Constitution Dock, Hobart TAS 7000, Australia

detail_description: The Tasmanian Travel & Information Centre in Hobart is a great starting point for exploring Tasmania. The staff, including Helena, Rashini, Chon, and Giovanna, are incredibly helpful and knowledgeable. They go above and beyond to provide assistance with recommendations, bookings, and travel advice. The center also offers tours of the Hobart district that are informative and well-managed. While the tour may involve some walking, it's easily manageable with a careful guide ensuring everyone stays together.
name: Tasmanian Travel & Information Centre
address: Corner of Elizabeth and, 20 Davey St, & Information Hub, Elizabeth St, Hobart TAS 7000, Australia

excerpt: Stylish independent picture house showing films since 1913, with rooftop screenings and a cool cafe.
detail_description: Step into the historic State Cinema in Hobart, a charming independent picture house that has been entertaining Tasmanians for over a century. With its art-deco facade and eight intimate screens, this cinematic gem offers a unique movie experience. The cozy seating and classic architecture transport you to another era, while the rooftop cinema and bar provide an opportunity for outdoor screenings and relaxation. Whether you're catching a new release or enjoying a classic flick, the diverse film selection ensures there's something for every movie lover.
name: State Cinema
address: 375 Elizabeth St, North Hobart TAS 7000, Australia

detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Hobart, the Allport Library and Museum of Fine Arts is a treasure trove for art enthusiasts and history buffs alike. Established through the generous bequest of Henry Allport in 1965, this cultural gem showcases an impressive collection that highlights convict artists and colonial landscape painters. With nearly 6,000 books and pamphlets housed within its library, visitors can delve into rare literature focused on the Australia-Pacific region alongside captivating antiques, photographs, and paintings.
name: Allport Library and Museum of Fine Arts
address: Ground Floor, 91 Murray St, Hobart TAS 7000, Australia

excerpt: Historic 1926 home featuring antiques & family heirlooms & a charming vintage garden.
detail_description: Markree House Museum and Garden is a historic 1926 home that offers a glimpse into the lives of Tasmanian nobility. The house, originally built for the wealthy Baldwin family, has been preserved along with its charming vintage garden, providing visitors with an understanding of early 20th-century Australian history. Donated to the city by Mr.
name: Markree House Museum and Garden

detail_description: St Joseph's Catholic Church is a welcoming place with ornate architecture and friendly parishioners. The church features regular services and is open to the public.
name: St. Joseph's Church
address: St Joseph's Catholic Church, 65 Harrington St, Hobart TAS 7000, Australia

detail_description: Located at 125 Macquarie Street, Hobart, Tasmania, the Hobart Synagogue is a historic site dating back to the mid-19th century. It is known for its splendid architecture and cavernous interior. The synagogue also offers regular services and features a small museum area along with seasonal religious events. Additionally, it is situated near the famous Salamanca Market and waterfront Georgian warehouses that have been repurposed into restaurants and galleries.
name: Hobart Synagogue
